# 🌐 HTML Level 3 – Notes

## 1. Tables in HTML
Used to display data in rows and columns.  
Tags: `<table>`, `<tr>`, `<th>`, `<td>`

**Example:**
```html
<table>
  <tr><th>Name</th><th>Age</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Ali</td><td>20</td></tr>
</table>
2. Semantics in Tables
Use <thead>, <tbody>, and <tfoot> to divide a table meaningfully.
✅ Enhances accessibility and structure.

Example:

html
Copy
Edit
<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Item</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody><tr><td>Pen</td></tr></tbody>
  <tfoot><tr><td>Total</td></tr></tfoot>
</table>
3. Colspan & Rowspan Attributes
colspan: Makes a cell span across multiple columns.

rowspan: Makes a cell span across multiple rows.

Example:

html
Copy
Edit
<tr>
  <td colspan="2">Merged Column</td>
</tr>
<tr>
  <td rowspan="2">Merged Row</td><td>Data</td>
</tr>
4. Practice Questions – Tables
Apply your knowledge of:

Table structure

Semantic tags

Row/column merging

5. Forms in HTML
Forms collect user input and send it to a server.
🛠️ Created using the <form> tag.
Often paired with <input>, <label>, and <button>.

Example:

html
Copy
Edit
<form>
  <input type="text" />
  <button type="submit">Submit</button>
</form>
6. Input – Form Element
The <input> tag is used for various types of user input.
Types include:

text

email

password

number

Example:

html
Copy
Edit
<input type="email" placeholder="Enter your email" />
7. Placeholders & Labels
placeholder: Shows hint text inside input.

<label>: Describes the input field, linked using for.

Example:

html
Copy
Edit
<label for="name">Name:</label>
<input type="text" id="name" placeholder="Enter your name" />
8. Button Element
The <button> tag is used to submit forms or trigger actions.
Types:

submit

reset

button

Example:

html
Copy
Edit
<button type="submit">Submit</button>
9. Name Attribute
The name attribute is used to reference form data after submission.
🎯 Important for backend/server-side processing.

Example:

html
Copy
Edit
<input type="text" name="username" />
10. Practice Questions – Form Basics
Exercises on:

Input fields

Labels

Name attribute

Form structure

11. Checkbox – Input Element
<input type="checkbox"> allows selecting one or more options.
✅ Useful for multiple choices like hobbies or skills.

Example:

html
Copy
Edit
<input type="checkbox" name="skill" value="HTML"> HTML
12. Radio – Input Element
<input type="radio"> allows selecting only one option in a group.
📌 Use the same name for grouping radio buttons.

Example:

html
Copy
Edit
<input type="radio" name="gender" value="male"> Male
<input type="radio" name="gender" value="female"> Female
13. Select – Input Element
Creates a dropdown list using <select> and <option>.

Example:

html
Copy
Edit
<select>
  <option value="html">HTML</option>
  <option value="css">CSS</option>
</select>
14. Range – Input Element
<input type="range"> creates a slider to select numeric values.
⚙️ Use min, max, and step attributes.

Example:

html
Copy
Edit
<input type="range" min="1" max="100" step="5">
15. Text Area
<textarea> is used for multi-line text input (e.g., comments or feedback).

Example:

html
Copy
Edit
<textarea rows="4" cols="30">Enter your feedback...</textarea>
16. Practice Questions – Input Elements
Practice topics:

Checkbox

Radio buttons

Select dropdown

Range slider

Text area